    "user_reviews": [
      {
        "title": "Speed! Amazing Upgrade",
        "text": "I just built my 4th Asus computer and upgraded to the I7 12700k. I cant believe how much of a jump it was from my old 8700. If you know anything about gaming, I was able to load a minecraft world on maximum chunks in less than a second. The fans made zero noise. I could not believe it. Intel is far in the lead right now. I tried one AMD build back about 6 years ago. I wanted to give them a shot. Out of all the computers I have built it was the only one where I had a failure. The processor died on me after just 2 years. No overclocking. I will always run Intel and I strongly recommend Asus as well. They have never failed me.",
        "user_name": "Andy B.",
        "source": "newegg.com",
        "rating": 5,
        "date": "4 years ago",
        "icon": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/shsm/AGYqVK1ZyijTXEawNQtS-HJ-BnApXNY9AaHbf79xkdaiKmtfyqFnZtHaPhPrz0cEczOKIAVZrg=w40-h40-c0x00000000-cc"
      },
      {
        "title": "Huge upgrade for me - very impressed - glad I waited",
        "text": "Blazing fast compared to my 8086k. WIFI 6 was a huge upgrade that had an immediate impact on my internet speed. M.2 is much faster and gained about 1.5k on my 3D Mark graphics score so either the PCIE upgrade did help or my previous CPU was bottlenecking my card a bit (3080). Overall, benchmark scores up roughly 20-25% total with the CPU score only up about 40%. Love this generation of Intel, they did a great job. Temps staying at or under 55C at full load. Unbelievably easy to change my processor and board. I just kept everything else the same. It loaded up on the first shot with preloaded drivers and I was good to go after logging into my Microsoft account. Couldn't have been easier there. I did do some cleanup but ASUS handled the rest. Cons - there are some DRM issues which is going to cause some games to crash on startup. I just happened to be playing Default Bravely 2 at the time. Going to have to wait for a fix before getting back into that. Oh well, not that big of a deal. Most of my games are fine but it's worth Googling 12700k DRM game list incompatibility so you're prepared for that. They're working on it.",
        "user_name": "Chris",
        "source": "newegg.com",
        "rating": 5,
        "date": "4 years ago",
        "icon": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/shsm/AGYqVK1hXtrG6nkujjNdZM7vLTdEuq138okUuXQVT7CEaxlYwKXr9-1rcsqS9zYT2do_7DD2HQ=w40-h40-c0x00000000-cc"
      },
      {
        "title": "A Nice Little Bump Coming from the 10700K",
        "text": "So let me just sum up... since I am coming from 10th Gen... The performance isn't mind blowing. Saw a nice bump in performance in the Adobe Suite, and about 8 FPS increase in AAA title GPU favored games. The main reason I got this WITH THE SPECIFIC ASUS STRIX Z690-A board that I picked is because I plan to stay with this little fella for the next 2-3 years and we have PCIe 5.0, cut outs to use pre-existing LGA 1150-1200 coolers (so I don't have to upgrade there, and if DDR5 is your jam, get the butter knife bubba... and spread it! Keep in mind, if you don't want to upgrade RAM (like I didn't just yet), pay attention to the specific board you buy because there are some that only support DDR4 and others that support DDR5... The ability to have a motherboard that supports both technologies is not a possibility.",
        "user_name": "Craig",
        "source": "bhphotovideo.com",
        "rating": 5,
        "date": "4 years ago",
        "icon": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/shsm/AGYqVK3oE_OFcDC-meCw4jmdhicefCKlAqo8Yx2RnA-jZhEwn9ox-oTvlCme-0g5MA708bJ1pA=w40-h40-c0x00000000-cc",
        "images": [
          "https://encrypted-tbn3.gstatic.com/shopping?q=tbn%3AANd9GcRXJhgYdtkUDgq3FQlFCdnMYOzbJYll2q2tvE9pX4Hro-VKnt6IfZaMKjk7C-He07EFylgVMPH6-BuAr7qNn0VDynULbGXM"
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Amazing!",
        "text": "This cpu is amazing. If you bought 11th gen....I feel for you. Chip runs great, temps are reasonable(using a 360 AIO). If you leave it at stock performance it great. Once you start overclocking, while there is some headroom, you will need pretty good cooling.\n\nOverall I'm very happy. I have this and a 12600k. If you are on a budget, that is really the cpu to get in my opinion.\n\nI have no need for the i9. It has a bit higher clocks and more E-cores. To me, nothing to get too excited about.\n\nI just hope Intel stays on this socket for 13th gen. From what I've read, that is the plan, but Intel hasn't really said anything officially.\n\nCheers!",
